Import and data checking

Import required library

tidyverse library ver. 1.3.1 is used for processing data.

This library include all required libraries:
- ggplot2 3.3.3, for data visualization.
- dplyr 1.0.5, for data manipulation.
- tidyr 1.1.3, for data tidying.
- readr 1.4.0, for data import.
- purrr 0.3.4, for functional programming.
as well as tibble ver. 3.1.0, stringr ver 1.4.0, ver. forcats 0.5.1

We used a countrycode package version 1.3.0 to translate NOC into country name. This was done so that the early participation of the country in the Olympiad (the team was called not by the name of the country) were taken into account in the same way as later (when the team had the name of the country).

- if we know the missing value for the participant (by ID) from other rows from the same year - we change it.

Gold medals received by women from 1980 to 2010

Women received 2249 gold medals from 1980 to 2010.

Number of participation times of athlete John Aalberg in the Olympic Games

John Aalberg participated in Olympic games 8 times, 4 times in the 1992 Winter Games and 4 times in the 1994 Winter Games.

Age groups of participants in the 2008 Olympic Games

The following boundaries were used to divide the participants into groups:
- group 0: Age < 15;
- group 1: Age 15-24;
- group 2: Age 25-34;
- group 3: Age 35-44;
- group 4: Age 45-55;
- group 5: Age > 55.

Each participant was counted only once, according to their ID number.

Among the participants from 15 to 55 years old, the smallest group is the 45-55 age group, the most numerous is the 25-34 age group.

Сhanging of the number of sports in the 2002 Olympics from the 1994 Olympic

The Olympic Games in 1994 and 2002 are the Winter Olympics. From 1994 to 2002, the number of Olympic winter sports increased.

The number of sports in 1994 was 12. The number of sports in 2002 was 15.

The number of sports at the 2002 Olympics, compared to 1994, has increased by 3 sports, or 25%.

Comparsion of the height, weight and ages of men and women who competed in the Winter Olympics

Sample size large enough to treat the distribution of height, weight and age as normally distributed values.

Each athlete is counted only once for each Games.

Height comparison

Welch Two Sample t-test (two sided) was performed. Alternative hypothesis - the athletes height depends on the sex.

The value of the t-statistic is -138.876 with 14445.2 degrees of freedom.
Welch Two Sample t-test showed that there was a significant difference between the male athletes height compared with female athletes height (p-value = 0 < 2.2 10^-16 ).

Weight comparison

Welch Two Sample t-test (two sided) was performed. Alternative hypothesis - the athletes weight depends on the sex.

The value of the t-statistic is -142.817 with 17998.9 degrees of freedom.
Welch Two Sample t-test showed that there was a significant difference between the male athletes weight compared with female athletes weight (p-value = 0 < 2.2 10^-16 ).

Age comparison

Welch Two Sample t-test (two sided) was performed. Alternative hypothesis - the athletes age depends on the sex.

The value of the t-statistic is -30.221 with 14747.7 degrees of freedom.
Welch Two Sample t-test showed that there was a significant difference between the male athletes age compared with female athletes age (p-value = 1.033492^{-194} < 2.2 10^-16 ).

Do we have any reason to believe that variables Team and Medal might be interrelated?

Some information about Team and Medal

The number of teams (countries) participating in the Olympic Games from 1896 to 2016 is 230.

Team has an average of 49 participants (with a standard deviation of 82.05) yearly.

Each team won an average of 10.36 medals of any type (with a standard deviation of 30.34) yearly.

During the observation period, each team received an average of 172.97 medals (with a standard deviation of 537.58.

Correlation

Hypothesis - there is a relationship between the team and the number of medals through the size of the team, that is, there is a relationship between the size of a team and the number of medals it won.

The number of participants in a team and the number of a team medals - do not have a normal distribution. Shapiro-Wilk normality test for p-value = 0 < 2.2 * 10^(-16) for team members distribution (with W = 0.598 and and the number of observations - 3840), and p-value = 0 < 2.2 * 10^(-16) for team medals distribution (with W = 0.373 and the number of observations - 3840).

A matrix of scatterplots for team members and number medals:

Kendall’s correlation. The Kendall’s rank correlation tau tests the null hypothesis ‘There is no correlation between the number of participants in team and the number of team medals’.

A Kendall’s rank correlation tau test showed that there is a marked degree of positive correlation (z = 53.077, tau = 0.64, and p = 0 < 2.2 * 10^(-16)) between the number of team members and the number of team medals.

Below are the top 10 countries with the largest average team size.

No medals

Hypothesis - there is a relationship between the team and the number of participants without medals through the size of the team, that is, there is a relationship between the size of a team and the number of medals it not won.

The number of participants in a team and the number of a team participants without medals - do not have a normal distribution. Shapiro-Wilk normality test for p-value = 0 < 2.2 * 10^(-16) for team members distribution (with W = 0.598 and the number of observations - 3841), and p-value = 0 < 2.2 * 10^(-16) for team participants without medals distribution (with W = 0.651 and the number of observations - 3841).

The Kendall’s rank correlation tau tests the null hypothesis ‘There is no correlation between the number of participants in team and the number of team losses’.

A Kendall’s rank correlation tau test showed that there is a strong positive correlation (z = 81.232, tau = 0.89, and p = 0 < 2.2 * 10^(-16)) between the number of team members and the number of their losses.

Does the number of male and female participants differ in teams at the Winter Olympics?

Each participant is counted only 1 time per game for each team.

The graph shows that the distribution of participants of both sexes does not have a normal distribution.

Shapiro-Wilk normality test for men in teams p-value = 0 < 2.2 * 10^(-16) for team members distribution (with W = 0.781 and the number of observations - 1007), and p-value = 0 < 2.2 * 10^(-16) for team participants without medals distribution (with W = 0.655 and the number of observations - 713).

The Mann-Whitney U tests the null hypothesis. An alternative hypothesis is that the number of male and female participants differ in teams at the Winter Olympics.

wilcox_winter <- wilcox.test(team_members~Sex,
                             data = winter_participants, 
                             alternative = "two.sided")

A Mann-Whitney U test showed that there was a significant difference (W = 2.9246{5}, p = 4.713574{-11}) between the number of male and female participants in teams at the Winter Olympics.

Is there a difference in the height of women at the winter and summer games?

We have a sufficient number of observations (40786 for Summer season and 8055 for Winter) to consider the distribution ofHeight variable of female athletes as a normal distribution, which can be seen on the graph.

Welch Two Sample t-test (two sided) was performed. Alternative hypothesis - there is a difference in the height of female athletes participating in the winter and summer games.

The value of the t-statistic is 39.264 with 13032.5 degrees of freedom.
Welch Two Sample t-test showed that there was a significant difference between the the height of female athletes participating in the winter or summer games (p-value = 8.440613^{-319}).
